newsitem.title: USA: CBOT corn ends up after fresh 5-1/2-month high set.
newsitem.headline: CBOT corn ends up after fresh 5-1/2-month high set.

text.p: CBOT corn futures closed higher on a surge to limit and near limit gains in soybeans, traders said.

Spot March corn set a fresh 5-1/2 month high at midday during the fund-sparked bull move in the soybean complex while fund and commercial buying rallied the corn market to roughly one half the 12 cent daily limit in the nearby contracts.
Traders said Cargill Inc was the key buyer of 12.0 million bushels of July.
The strong market was evident despite the imminent release of a key government supply/demand report.
"Basically corn is following beans. We don't have a problem with feedgrain stocks but bean stocks are another story," a trader said.

USDA at 0730 CST/1330 GMT Tuesday will release its March Supply/Demand Report and analysts were expecting the government to trim five million to 10 million bushels of soybeans from the current outlook of 140 million bushels for 1996-97 U.S. carryout.
Corn futures closed 1-1/2 to six cents per bushel higher, with March up six at $3.12. May closed 5-3/4 cents higher at $3.09-3/4 and December closed 3-1/2 higher at $2.91-1/2.
